    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2440558392" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2440558392" />
    <a title="Fiona" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5460316-fiona"><img alt="Fiona" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1487216044p2/5460316.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2440558392?book_show_action=true">Jan 23, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fiona" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fiona" href="/user/show/5460316-fiona">Fiona</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2440558392" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9550322531402617959">Where to even begin - two books in and I&apos;m a complete Mieville convert!<br/><br/>Perdido St Station was so vivid in my mind&apos;s eye - when I saw the reviews for The Scar that claimed they liked it more, I thought I&apos;d be the odd one out. But everything I loved in PSS is here, only at sea, with pirates who free the Remade, who not only accept but appreciate their differences. Sure, there&apos;s the press-ganging, but compared to the totalitarianism that seems to be the vogue in Bas-Lag, what&apos;s a little kidnapping-</span>
  <span id="freeText9550322531402617959" style="display:none">Where to even begin - two books in and I'm a complete Mieville convert!<br /><br />Perdido St Station was so vivid in my mind's eye - when I saw the reviews for The Scar that claimed they liked it more, I thought I'd be the odd one out. But everything I loved in PSS is here, only at sea, with pirates who free the Remade, who not only accept but appreciate their differences. Sure, there's the press-ganging, but compared to the totalitarianism that seems to be the vogue in Bas-Lag, what's a little kidnapping-to-a-socialist-haven between friends?<br /><br />Mieville's imagination was hardly constrained in book one, but moving out from New Crobuzon into the larger world of Bas-Lag seems to have offered him even further heights for it to spring to. This world is so gloriously weird and spooky, filled with races and creatures that could almost be whimsical if it wasn't for that punk edge.<br /><br />Bellis, too, has to be one of my favourite protagonists of all time. She's spiky and self-contained, happy on her own and consistent in that happiness. She makes bad decisions and incredibly smart ones, sometimes simultaneously, she is a lean, mean, linguistics machine, and I'm here for it all. Tanner may have my heart, but Bellis has my heart <i>and</i> my mind.<br /><br />My Mieville journey may still be very new, but it is very, very far from over.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9550322531402617959" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


